<div class="content">
  <h2>How the Sourdough Timer Works</h2>
  <p>This tool works <strong>backward from your desired bake time</strong>. Tell it when you want bread out of the oven, and it calculates the exact start time for every step — from feeding your starter all the way through scoring and baking.</p>
  <p>The schedule automatically adjusts based on your <strong>room temperature</strong>. Warmer kitchens (above 75°F) speed up fermentation significantly, while cooler environments (below 68°F) slow things down. The timer accounts for this so your dough doesn't over- or under-proof.</p>

  <h2>Same-Day vs. Cold Retard Method</h2>
  <p><strong>Same-day baking</strong> means you mix, bulk ferment, shape, proof at room temperature, and bake all in one session. This is faster (10-14 hours total) but gives you less scheduling flexibility and a milder flavor.</p>
  <p><strong>Cold retard</strong> is the preferred method for most home bakers. After shaping, the dough goes into the fridge overnight (12-18 hours). Benefits include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>More complex, tangy flavor from slow fermentation</li>
    <li>Easier to score — cold dough holds its shape better under the blade</li>
    <li>Flexible timing — bake anytime the next morning or even up to 48 hours later</li>
    <li>Better oven spring from the temperature differential</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Understanding Temperature & Fermentation</h2>
  <p>Sourdough fermentation is driven by wild yeast and lactic acid bacteria, both of which are highly sensitive to temperature. As a rough guide:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>65°F (18°C):</strong> Very slow fermentation. Bulk may take 6-8 hours. Great for overnight room-temp proofing.</li>
    <li><strong>72°F (22°C):</strong> Standard. Bulk fermentation around 4-5 hours. Most recipes are written for this temperature.</li>
    <li><strong>78°F (26°C):</strong> Fast. Bulk in 3-4 hours. Watch carefully to avoid over-proofing.</li>
    <li><strong>85°F+ (29°C+):</strong> Very fast. Consider reducing starter percentage or using cold water.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Tips for Using This Schedule</h2>
  <p>Remember: <strong>watch the dough, not the clock</strong>. This timer gives you estimates, but your dough is the real indicator. Look for 30-50% volume increase, a domed top, visible bubbles on the sides, and a jiggly texture to know bulk fermentation is done.</p>
  <p>If you enable <strong>browser notifications</strong>, you'll get an alert before each step so you never miss a stretch and fold or forget to preheat your oven.</p>
</div>

